We use supabase for the database. There's a users table, a user_preferences table, a conversations table, and a messages table.

users table:

id | int8
created_at | timestamp | now()
email | text
user_id | text
google_assistant_user_id | text

the user ID is given by google auth, and is a unique identifier for the user.

user_preferences table:

id | int8
created_at | timestamp | now()
user_id | text | foreign key to users.user_id
preferences | jsonb
encrypted_preferences | bytea
last_updated | timestamp | now()

conversations table:

id | int8
user_id | text | foreign key to users.user_id
title | text
created_at | timestamp | now()
last_message_time | timestamp | now()
source | text | 'app', 'voice', or 'web'
google_session_id | text
updated_at | timestamp | now()
optimistic_chat_id | text

This table also has indexes
- idx_conversations_user_id on conversations(user_id)
- idx_conversations_last_message on conversations(user_id, last_message_time DESC)
- idx_conversations_user_updated on conversations(user_id, updated_at DESC)

messages table:

id | int8
conversation_id | int8 | foreign key to conversations.id
content | text
message_sender | text | 'USER' or 'ASSISTANT' (renamed from message_type)
content_type | text | 'text', 'tool_use', 'tool_result', or 'mixed' | default 'text' | NOT NULL
tool_content | jsonb | NULL for text messages, populated for tool-related messages
timestamp | timestamp | now()
updated_at | timestamp | now()
request_id | text
cancelled | timestamp | NULL if not cancelled

Note: For text messages, content contains the plain text. For tool messages, tool_content contains the structured JSON (tool_use, tool_result blocks). This allows storing full Claude API conversation context including tool execution history.

This table also has indexes
- idx_messages_conversation_id on messages(conversation_id)
- idx_messages_timestamp on messages(conversation_id, timestamp ASC)
- idx_messages_conversation_updated on messages(conversation_id, updated_at DESC)

sync_metadata table:

id | int8
user_id | text | foreign key to users.user_id
entity_type | text | 'conversations', 'messages'
entity_id | int8 | foreign key to conversations.id or messages.id
last_sync_timestamp | timestamp
created_at | timestamp | now()
updated_at | timestamp | now()

the combination of user_id, entity_type, and entity_id is unique.

This table also has indexes

screen_agent_ui_dumps table:

id | int8
created_at | timestamp with time zone | now()
user_id | text | foreign key to users.user_id
dump_reason | text | NOT NULL | tag like 'whatsapp_chat_not_found', 'ytmusic_play_error'
error_message | text | human-readable error description
ui_hierarchy | text | NOT NULL | full UI dump text content
package_name | text | app package where error occurred (e.g., 'com.whatsapp')
device_model | text | e.g., 'Pixel 7'
device_manufacturer | text | e.g., 'Google'
android_version | text | e.g., '14'
screen_width | integer | screen width in pixels
screen_height | integer | screen height in pixels
app_version | text | Whiz app version
conversation_id | int8 | foreign key to conversations.id (nullable)
recent_actions | jsonb | default '[]' | last 5 screen agent actions
screen_agent_context | jsonb | optional extra debug info
is_emulator | boolean | nullable | true if the dump came from an Android emulator; autofix trigger is skipped when true
expected_failure | boolean | default false | true for errors that are expected (e.g. contact not found); autofix trigger is skipped when true

This table stores UI hierarchy dumps captured when the screen agent encounters navigation failures, used for debugging and improving screen agent code.

wake_word_audio_clips table:

id | int8
created_at | timestamp with time zone | now()
user_id | text | foreign key to users.user_id
phrase | text | NOT NULL | e.g. 'hey_whiz'
confidence | double precision | NOT NULL | Vosk confidence score
accepted | boolean | NOT NULL | whether detection met the threshold
detection_timestamp | int8 | NOT NULL | epoch millis when detection fired
raw_vosk_json | text | full Vosk JSON result
storage_path | text | NOT NULL | path in Supabase Storage bucket 'wake-word-audio'
file_size_bytes | integer | WAV file size
classifier_score | double precision | default -1.0 | ONNX classifier probability score (-1.0 if classifier not available)

This table stores metadata for wake word detection audio clips. The actual WAV files are stored in the Supabase Storage bucket 'wake-word-audio'. Both accepted and rejected detections are captured for training data.

This table has indexes:
- idx_ww_audio_user on wake_word_audio_clips(user_id)
- idx_ww_audio_created on wake_word_audio_clips(created_at DESC)

policies:

CREATE POLICY "Service role full access" ON wake_word_audio_clips FOR ALL USING (true) WITH CHECK (true);

Use `whizvoice/export_wake_word_audio.py` to download all clips to local disk and purge from Supabase.

This table has indexes:
- idx_ui_dumps_user_id on screen_agent_ui_dumps(user_id)
- idx_ui_dumps_dump_reason on screen_agent_ui_dumps(dump_reason)
- idx_ui_dumps_created_at on screen_agent_ui_dumps(created_at DESC)

policies:

CREATE POLICY "Service role can do everything" ON screen_agent_ui_dumps
    FOR ALL
    USING (true)
    WITH CHECK (true);

Note that supabase has had some SQL editor functions for the encryption and decryption of the encrypted_preferences column in the user_preferences table; that looks like this:

function for getting a specific key's value from regular (not encrypted) preferences

CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION get_preference_value(
   p_user_id TEXT,
   p_target_key TEXT
)
RETURNS TEXT AS $$
BEGIN
   RETURN (SELECT preferences ->> p_target_key FROM user_preferences WHERE user_id = p_user_id);
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

function for setting a specific key's value in regular (not encrypted) preferences

CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION set_preference_value(
   p_user_id TEXT,
   p_target_key TEXT,
   p_value TEXT -- Value to set, will be treated as a JSON string value
)
RETURNS VOID AS $$
BEGIN
   UPDATE user_preferences
   SET preferences = jsonb_set(
         COALESCE(preferences, '{}'::jsonb), -- Ensure 'preferences' is not NULL
         ARRAY[p_target_key], 
         to_jsonb(p_value), -- Convert text to a JSON string value
         true -- Create the key if it doesn't exist
      ),
      last_updated = CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
   WHERE user_id = p_user_id;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

function for getting decrypted preferences

CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION get_decrypted_preferences(
   p_user_id TEXT,
   p_encryption_key TEXT
)
RETURNS TEXT AS $$
DECLARE
   decrypted_prefs TEXT;
BEGIN
   -- Ensure pgcrypto extension is available
   CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS pgcrypto;


   SELECT pgp_sym_decrypt(encrypted_preferences, p_encryption_key)
   INTO decrypted_prefs
   FROM user_preferences
   WHERE user_id = p_user_id;


   -- Returns the decrypted text (JSON string)
   -- Returns NULL if no user row is found
   -- Returns NULL or throws an error if decryption fails (e.g., wrong key, corrupted data)
   RETURN decrypted_prefs;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

function for getting a specific key's value from decrypted preferences

CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION get_decrypted_preference_key(
   p_user_id TEXT,
   p_encryption_key TEXT,
   p_target_key TEXT  -- The key whose value you want to retrieve
)
RETURNS TEXT AS $$
DECLARE
   decrypted_json_text TEXT;
   key_value TEXT;
BEGIN
   -- Ensure pgcrypto extension is available
   CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS pgcrypto;


   -- Decrypt the entire preference object first
   SELECT pgp_sym_decrypt(encrypted_preferences, p_encryption_key)
   INTO decrypted_json_text
   FROM user_preferences
   WHERE user_id = p_user_id;


   -- If decryption was successful and returned text...
   IF decrypted_json_text IS NOT NULL THEN
       BEGIN
           -- Try to cast the decrypted text to jsonb
           -- and then extract the specific key's value as text using ->>
           SELECT (decrypted_json_text::jsonb) ->> p_target_key
           INTO key_value;


       EXCEPTION WHEN OTHERS THEN
           -- Handle potential errors during casting (if not valid JSON)
           -- or key extraction (if key doesn't exist).
           -- Log warning is useful for debugging in Supabase logs.
           RAISE WARNING 'Error processing decrypted JSON for user % key %: %', p_user_id, p_target_key, SQLERRM;
           key_value := NULL; -- Return NULL if processing fails
       END;
   ELSE
       -- No record found or initial decryption failed
       key_value := NULL;
   END IF;


   RETURN key_value; -- Returns the value as TEXT, or NULL if not found/error
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

function for setting a specific key's value in encrypted preferences

    CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION set_encrypted_preference_key(
       p_user_id TEXT,
       p_target_key TEXT,
       p_value TEXT, -- Value is passed as text, will be inserted into JSON
       p_encryption_key TEXT
    )
    RETURNS VOID AS $$
    DECLARE
       current_encrypted_blob BYTEA;
       decrypted_json_text TEXT;
       updated_json_blob JSONB;
       new_encrypted_blob BYTEA;
    BEGIN
       CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS pgcrypto;

       SELECT encrypted_preferences INTO current_encrypted_blob
       FROM user_preferences WHERE user_id = p_user_id;

       IF current_encrypted_blob IS NULL THEN
           decrypted_json_text := '{}'; 
       ELSE
           BEGIN
               decrypted_json_text := pgp_sym_decrypt(current_encrypted_blob, p_encryption_key);
           EXCEPTION WHEN OTHERS THEN
               -- Handle potential error if key is wrong or data is corrupt
               RAISE WARNING 'Error decrypting preferences for user %: %. Assuming empty preferences.', p_user_id, SQLERRM;
               decrypted_json_text := '{}';
           END;
       END IF;
       
       IF decrypted_json_text IS NULL OR decrypted_json_text = '' THEN
          decrypted_json_text := '{}';
       END IF;

       -- Convert to JSONB, set the key. to_jsonb() ensures p_value is treated as a JSON string value.
       -- If p_value itself could be a complex JSON structure, use p_value::jsonb instead of to_jsonb(p_value)
       updated_json_blob := jsonb_set(decrypted_json_text::jsonb, ARRAY[p_target_key], to_jsonb(p_value), true);

       new_encrypted_blob := pgp_sym_encrypt(updated_json_blob::TEXT, p_encryption_key);

       UPDATE user_preferences
       SET encrypted_preferences = new_encrypted_blob,
           last_updated = CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
       WHERE user_id = p_user_id;
    END;
    $$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

function for setting entire encrypted preferences

CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION set_encrypted_preferences(
   p_user_id TEXT,
   p_preferences_payload JSONB, -- The entire JSON object to be encrypted and stored
   p_encryption_key TEXT
)
RETURNS VOID AS $$
DECLARE
   new_encrypted_blob BYTEA;
BEGIN
   -- Ensure pgcrypto extension is available
   CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS pgcrypto;

   -- Encrypt the provided payload
   new_encrypted_blob := pgp_sym_encrypt(p_preferences_payload::TEXT, p_encryption_key);

   -- Update only the encrypted_preferences and last_updated columns
   UPDATE user_preferences
   SET 
       encrypted_preferences = new_encrypted_blob,
       last_updated = CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
   WHERE user_id = p_user_id;

   -- Optional: Check if the update actually found a row, if needed for robust error handling from calling code.
   -- IF NOT FOUND THEN
   --    RAISE WARNING 'User % not found in user_preferences. No encrypted preferences updated.', p_user_id;
   -- END IF;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;





















triggers to automatically update updated_at timestamp:

CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION update_updated_at_column()
RETURNS TRIGGER AS $$
BEGIN
    NEW.updated_at = NOW();
    RETURN NEW;
END;
$$ language 'plpgsql';

triggers to auto-update timestamps:

CREATE TRIGGER update_conversations_updated_at BEFORE UPDATE ON conversations
    FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE FUNCTION update_updated_at_column();

CREATE TRIGGER update_messages_updated_at BEFORE UPDATE ON messages
    FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE FUNCTION update_updated_at_column();

-- Auto-update conversation last_message_time when a new message is inserted.
-- This triggers the existing update_conversations_updated_at BEFORE UPDATE trigger,
-- which also sets updated_at = NOW(), enabling incremental sync detection.
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION update_conversation_on_new_message()
RETURNS TRIGGER AS $$
BEGIN
    UPDATE conversations
    SET last_message_time = NOW()
    WHERE id = NEW.conversation_id;
    RETURN NEW;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

CREATE TRIGGER update_conversation_timestamps_on_message_insert
    AFTER INSERT ON messages
    FOR EACH ROW
    EXECUTE FUNCTION update_conversation_on_new_message();

policies:

CREATE POLICY "Users can view their own sync metadata" ON sync_metadata
    FOR SELECT USING (user_id = current_setting('app.current_user_id', true));

CREATE POLICY "Users can insert their own sync metadata" ON sync_metadata
    FOR INSERT WITH CHECK (user_id = current_setting('app.current_user_id', true));

CREATE POLICY "Users can update their own sync metadata" ON sync_metadata
    FOR UPDATE USING (user_id = current_setting('app.current_user_id', true));

-- RPC Function to atomically clear a token and verify it was cleared
-- This version works with your existing encrypted preferences functions

CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION clear_and_verify_encrypted_token(
  p_user_id TEXT,
  p_key_name TEXT,
  p_encryption_key TEXT
)
RETURNS JSON
LANGUAGE plpgsql
SECURITY DEFINER
SET search_path = public
AS $$
DECLARE
  v_result JSON;
  v_old_value TEXT;
  v_new_value TEXT;
BEGIN
  -- First, get the current value (if any) using your existing function
  v_old_value := get_decrypted_preference_key(p_user_id, p_encryption_key, p_key_name);
  
  -- Clear the token by setting it to NULL using your existing function
  -- Your set_encrypted_preference_key function handles NULL by converting to empty JSON
  -- We need to actually remove the key from the JSON
  DECLARE
    current_encrypted_blob BYTEA;
    decrypted_json_text TEXT;
    updated_json_blob JSONB;
    new_encrypted_blob BYTEA;
  BEGIN
    -- Get current encrypted blob
    SELECT encrypted_preferences INTO current_encrypted_blob
    FROM user_preferences WHERE user_id = p_user_id;
    
    IF current_encrypted_blob IS NOT NULL THEN
      -- Decrypt current preferences
      BEGIN
        decrypted_json_text := pgp_sym_decrypt(current_encrypted_blob, p_encryption_key);
      EXCEPTION WHEN OTHERS THEN
        -- If decryption fails, start with empty object
        decrypted_json_text := '{}';
      END;
      
      -- Remove the key from the JSON object (this actually clears it)
      updated_json_blob := (decrypted_json_text::jsonb) - p_key_name;
      
      -- Re-encrypt and save
      new_encrypted_blob := pgp_sym_encrypt(updated_json_blob::TEXT, p_encryption_key);
      
      UPDATE user_preferences
      SET encrypted_preferences = new_encrypted_blob,
          last_updated = CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
      WHERE user_id = p_user_id;
    END IF;
  END;
  
  -- Now verify it's actually cleared by reading it back
  v_new_value := get_decrypted_preference_key(p_user_id, p_encryption_key, p_key_name);
  
  -- Build result JSON
  RETURN json_build_object(
    'success', true,
    'token_cleared', (v_new_value IS NULL OR v_new_value = ''),
    'message', CASE 
      WHEN v_new_value IS NULL OR v_new_value = '' THEN 'Token successfully cleared'
      ELSE 'Warning: Token may not have been cleared properly'
    END,
    'old_value_existed', (v_old_value IS NOT NULL AND v_old_value != ''),
    'new_value_is_null', (v_new_value IS NULL),
    'new_value_is_empty', (v_new_value = '')
  );

EXCEPTION
  WHEN OTHERS THEN
    -- Log the error and return failure
    RAISE WARNING 'Error in clear_and_verify_encrypted_token: %', SQLERRM;
    RETURN json_build_object(
      'success', false,
      'token_cleared', false,
      'message', 'Error: ' || SQLERRM,
      'old_value_existed', false
    );
END;
$$;

-- Grant execute permission to authenticated users
GRANT EXECUTE ON FUNCTION clear_and_verify_encrypted_token TO authenticated;

-- Add a comment to document the function
COMMENT ON FUNCTION clear_and_verify_encrypted_token IS 
'Atomically clears an encrypted preference token by removing the key from the JSON object.
Returns JSON with success status and confirmation that token was cleared.
This ensures read-after-write consistency by performing both operations in a single transaction.
Requires the encryption key used for the user preferences.';


-- Create a trigger to hard delete messages when a conversation is soft-deleted
-- This ensures messages are cleaned up even with soft deletes

-- Create the trigger function
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION delete_messages_on_conversation_soft_delete()
RETURNS TRIGGER AS $$
BEGIN
    -- If deleted_at is being set (was NULL, now has a value)
    IF OLD.deleted_at IS NULL AND NEW.deleted_at IS NOT NULL THEN
        -- Delete all messages for this conversation
        DELETE FROM messages WHERE conversation_id = NEW.id;
        RAISE NOTICE 'Deleted messages for soft-deleted conversation %', NEW.id;
    END IF;
    RETURN NEW;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- Create the trigger
DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS soft_delete_conversation_messages ON conversations;
CREATE TRIGGER soft_delete_conversation_messages
    AFTER UPDATE ON conversations
    FOR EACH ROW
    EXECUTE FUNCTION delete_messages_on_conversation_soft_delete();

-- Function to prevent inserting messages into soft-deleted conversations
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION
prevent_messages_to_deleted_conversations()
RETURNS trigger
LANGUAGE plpgsql
AS $function$
BEGIN
    -- Check if the conversation is soft-deleted
    IF EXISTS (
        SELECT 1 FROM conversations
        WHERE id = NEW.conversation_id
        AND deleted_at IS NOT NULL
    ) THEN
        RAISE EXCEPTION 'Cannot insert message into soft-deleted conversation %', NEW.conversation_id;
    END IF;
    RETURN NEW;
END;
$function$;

-- Create trigger to run before inserting messages
DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS prevent_insert_to_deleted_conversation ON
messages;
CREATE TRIGGER prevent_insert_to_deleted_conversation
    BEFORE INSERT ON messages
    FOR EACH ROW
    EXECUTE FUNCTION prevent_messages_to_deleted_conversations();
